                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="13249" author="daneverton" created="Tue, 17 May 2005 00:45:21 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I don&apos;t think this is limited to Spring webflow. We have a few autowire byName beans that rely on MessageSource implementations and they do not work with Spring 1.2. The setter for the property relying on the MessageSource is never called. This worked fine in RC2.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13269" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Wed, 18 May 2005 04:44:34 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I can confirm that this a core issue: dependencies of type MessageSource are ignored as of Spring 1.2 final, which was intended for to avoid dependency checking failure in case of a MessageSourceAware bean.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The side effect on autowiring was not deliberate, actually: unfortunately, an ignored dependency type is ignored there too... I&apos;ll have a look at fixing this in the coming days.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A workaround for the time being is either to explicitly wire that property, or to let your bean implement Spring&apos;s MessageSourceAware interface (which defined exactly a setMessageSource method).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juergen&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13283" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Wed, 18 May 2005 19:57:45 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I&apos;ve fixed this through introducing &quot;ignored dependency interfaces&quot; in addition to the existing &quot;ignored dependency types&quot;. An ApplicationContext registers ApplicationContextAware, MessageSourceAware, etc as &quot;ignored dependency interfaces&quot; now, ignoring any setter methods defined there. Setters that are not defined by these interfaces are still satisfied, even if their type is an ApplicationContext, MessageSource, etc.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juergen&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
